  "reference_nair_concepts": {
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\nHepatitis C.\nHISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS\nBruce Ward is a pleasant 60-year-old male who presents to the clinic today following a positive result in a hepatitis C antibody test. He was sent to obtain the hepatitis C antibody test as part of a routine physical. He states he is anxious with the results and denies he has ever been diagnosed with hepatitis C. The patient admits to intravenous drug use in the past; however, he notes it has been longer than 15 years since his last usage. He also reports a history of heavy alcohol use. He continues to drink a beer on occasion. The patient currently smokes 1 to 2 cigarettes per day. He notes he used to smoke more and is having difficulty with complete cessation.\nMEDICAL HISTORY\nThe patient denies any significant past medical history.\nSOCIAL HISTORY\nThe patient is married with children. He reports history of IV drug use 15 years ago. He currently drinks beer occasionally. The patient reports smoking 1 to 2 cigarettes per day.\nFAMILY HISTORY\nHe reports a family history of high blood pressure, diabetes, and depression.",
        "medical_concepts": [
          "hepatitis C",
          "hepatitis C antibody test",
          "intravenous drug use",
          "heavy alcohol use",
          "beer",
          "smoking",
          "cigarettes",
          "difficulty with smoking cessation",
          "high blood pressure",
          "diabetes",
          "depression"
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "MEDICATIONS\nPatient denies taking any current medications.\nVITALS\nAll vital signs are within normal limits.\nPHYSICAL EXAM\nCONSTITUTIONAL: In no apparent distress.\nCV: Regular rate and rhythm. Grade 2 out of 6 systolic ejection murmur is appreciated.\nRESPIRATORY: Lungs are clear without wheezes, rales, or rhonchi.\nGI/GU: Abdomen is soft with no hepatosplenomegaly. Bowel sounds are present.\nSKIN: No jaundice.",
        "medical_concepts": [
          "vital signs",
          "systolic ejection murmur",
          "wheezes",
          "rales",
          "rhonchi",
          "hepatosplenomegaly",
          "bowel sounds",
          "jaundice"
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "RESULTS\nThe HCV antibody test was reviewed today and is positive.\nLiver panel revealed an elevated AST at 39 U/L. The ALT, albumin, and total bilirubin were all within normal limits.\nASSESSMENT\nHepatitis C.\nPLAN\nAfter reviewing the patient's laboratory findings today, I have had a lengthy discussion with him in regard to his current symptoms. His initial labs were consistent with a hepatitis C diagnosis. I have recommended that we confirm the diagnosis with additional blood work including checking his hepatitis C RNA and HCV genotype. I have also recommended that we obtain an ultrasound elastography to evaluate for fibrosis of the liver.\nThe patient is married with children and is concerned about their hepatitis C status. I advised the patient that his family should be screened and we will assist him with setting appointments with their primary care physician.\nINSTRUCTIONS\nThe patient will follow up with me in 3 weeks to review his results and discuss further treatment.",
